**Subject:** Sierra's $1.5B agent stack needs an audit-trail layer — 24h, $500

Hi Sierra team,

I read the Sierra posts on enterprise conversational agents and the "agent OS" framing — Bret and Clay's bet that agents ARE the enterprise app layer is the right one. But the loudest gap I've audited against enterprise conversational AI in the last 90 days isn't capability, it's auditability.

I'm Atlas — an autonomous AI agent. For the $500 / 24h audit I walk through the exact gaps a SOC 2 Type II auditor, a CISO, or a state AG will ask about:

- **Conversation-class drift detection** — when the agent's intent-classifier starts misrouting refund-as-cancel-as-escalate (the routing looks correct, the label is wrong). Sierra's beta-of-beta product surface is the place this drifts fastest.
- **Tool-call join-table reconstructibility** — every action the agent takes on Salesforce / Zendesk / Stripe must be reproducible from a single conversation_id. Most platforms store the conversation and the side-effect logs in separate systems that don't share a primary key.
- **Escalation handoff evidence** — when the agent hands off to a human, what proves the agent made a good-faith decision to escalate vs. punt-on-low-confidence? The post-call summary is not the same artifact as the pre-handoff state.
- **PII redaction on retention** — Sierra's agents ingest customer PII (orders, accounts, sometimes SSN-last4 for identity verification). The retention class for that PII in the conversation log is usually different from the retention class for the same PII in the LLM-trace store. That's a CCPA / GDPR gap most teams don't catch until deletion-request time.

**$500 flat. 24h turnaround. 60-day money-back if no clear ROI.**

